[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering dynamic coverage**\n\nI'm thinking that dynamic coverage might be set up on line 31 of the ClassLoaderClassResolver. It seems like if the fallback fails with a ClassNotFoundException, it still executes until it reaches that call site on line 31. \n\nBut I want to ensure that the test passes despite this failure. It’s intriguing to analyze how the execution flow behaves in this context, while also making sure everything aligns properly for testing!\n\n**Evaluating class loading in tests**\n\nIt seems like it's okay to reach the call site, but having high coverage should include a successful fallback if possible. I wonder if a test that resolves a non-existent class could be acceptable, even if it’s version agnostic. I think better behavior would be to check for both binary name success and malformed descriptor fallbacks. We might want to adjust our second test to assert exceptions for a deliberately missing package. However, that doesn't specifically check Class.forName fallback.\n\n**Examining dynamic call sites**\n\nI need to focus on dynamic call sites, particularly at line 29 with ClassLoader.loadClass and line 31 for Class.forName. If I resolve a missing class, the first and second cases would be covered with a single test. I could add a test for both positive loadClass and fallback failure using an assertion for ClassNotFoundException. I’m curious if Class.forName in native might require metadata, and whether \"missing class\" names include active classes. Should I replace the int array test or add a third test?", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f60718b29e5bc3b0169f0d0f8bad881919290abaa5af72205\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp8NEXKAMB1HN7vaR9HMAuduGSVCWWSzay0CLAbaPh2Hb-gwF0PsVReZN_erAMW3u0HbhPYYlxETAdzrs0oq-BUqQdsrKyue97oUhRYJO4dWDqI86dMgr9l-Fnnj9-Zh0ypxBBYE4SE7lg4EOjVKcWVqoXM7nPXj-icDupuDe9HiLDmre5lrE1heSiOIoHdSe